ANALYTICAL CHECKLIST
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. PLOT ARCHITECTURE
   • Causal chain vs. associative/juxtapositional?
   • Time: linear, circular, nested, or multi-threaded?
   • Major turnings: inciting incident, midpoint, climax, false climax
   • Minimum set of events that still produces the same ending

2. TEMPORAL STRUCTURE
   • Story time vs. discourse time (duration, order, frequency — Genette)
   • Anachronies: flashbacks (analepsis), flash-forwards (prolepsis), ellipses
   • Rhythm: scenes of expansion vs. summary compression

3. PERSPECTIVE & VOICE
   • Focalization (who sees): zero / internal / external
   • Narrator reliability, distance, knowledge limits
   • Shifts in point-of-view and what they buy

4. CHARACTER FUNCTION
   • Protagonist desire line and its transformations
   • Actantial roles (Greimas): Subject / Object / Sender / Receiver / Helper / Opponent
   • Flat vs. round • static vs. dynamic • foil systems

5. THEMATIC / SEMANTIC STRUCTURE
   • Binary oppositions and their mediation (Lévi-Strauss)
   • Recurring motifs, symbols, and their transformation rules
   • Closure mechanisms: resolve / open / generate new problems?

6. DISCOURSE vs. STORY
   • What is told vs. how it is told
   • Gaps the reader must fill (Iser’s “blanks”)
   • Metanarrative commentary or self-reference

QUICK PRACTICAL METHOD
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  1. Extract the fabula      (chronological event list)
  2. Map the sjuzhet         (order and emphasis of presentation)
  3. Identify the dominant organizing principle:
        – Goal-oriented causality?
        – Character revelation?
        – Thematic juxtaposition?
        – Formal / geometric constraint?
  4. Locate points of maximum information density
     and maximum uncertainty
  5. Ask: “What would break if I removed or reordered X?”

